{"cursor":"14105","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Presence' is a theoretical concept describing the extent to which media\nrepresent the world (in both physical and social environments). Presence is further described by Matthew Lombard and Theresa\nDitton as âan illusion that a mediated experience is not mediated.\" Today, it often considers the effect that people experience\nwhen they interact with a computer-mediated or computer-generated\nenvironment. The conceptualization of presence borrows\nfrom multiple fields including communication, computer science, psychology,\nscience, engineering, philosophy, and the arts. The concept of presence accounts\nfor a variety of computer applications and Web-based entertainment today that\nare developed on the fundamentals of the phenomenon, in order to give people the\nsense of, as Sheridan called it, âbeing there.\" \n","linknr":210,"url":"Presence_(telepresence)","recorded":1362478002,"links":15,"instances":["sociology"],"pdf":["http://www.presence-research.org/papers/steuer92defining.pdf","http://www.presence-research.org/papers/steuer92defining.pdf"],"categories":["Telepresence","Virtual reality","Media technology","Cognitive science","Philosophy of mind"],"headings":["Evolution of 'presence' as a concept","Case studies","Presence in popular culture","See also","References","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/0a/Typology_of_human_experience_in_virtual.png/220px-Typology_of_human_experience_in_virtual.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/2/23/Lombard_conceptulization_of_presence.png/220px-Lombard_conceptulization_of_presence.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/7/75/Lee_typology_of_virtual_experience.png/220px-Lee_typology_of_virtual_experience.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/s